{{NCAATeamSeason |Mode = Basketball |sex = women |Year = 2009-10 |Prev year = 2008-09 |Next year = 2010-11 |Team = Penn State Nittany Lions |Image = |Image_size = 150 |Conference = Big Ten |division = |ShortConference = Big Ten |CoachRank = |APRank = |Record = 17-14 |ConfRecord = 9-11 |HeadCoach = [[Coquese Washington]] |AsstCoach1 = Itoro Coleman |AsstCoach2 = Kia Damon |AsstCoach3 = Maren Walseth |StadiumArena = [[Bryce Jordan Center]] |caBigity = |Champion = Maine Classic Champions |BowlTourney = [[2010 Women's National Invitation Tournament|WNIT]] |BowlTourneyResult = First Round }} The '''2009â10 Penn State Lady Lions basketball team''' represented [[Pennsylvania State University]] in the [[2009â10 NCAA Division I women's basketball season]]. It was the 46th season of Lady Lions basketball. The Lady Lions, a member of the [[Big Ten Conference]], finished the season tied for sixth in the conference. They advanced to the [[2010 Women's National Invitation Tournament|WNIT]], losing in the first round to [[Hofstra Pride|Hofstra]].
==Offseason== *July 21: Julia Trogele recently completed her stint playing with the U20 German National team at the 2009 European U20 Women's Championships in Poland. The Germans finished in eighth place in the tournament, a marked improvement from the 12th-place finish last year. In nine games, Trogele finished second on the team with a 10.7 scoring average. She also led the Germans in rebounding (6.4), steals (1.9) and blocks (0.6). She connected on 46.3% of her shots (37-80) and 88% of her free throws (22-25).<ref>http://www.gopsusports.com/sports/w-baskbl/spec-rel/072109aaa.html</ref> *July 23: Basketball head coach Coquese Washington gave birth to a baby girl. Her name is Rhaiyna Kamille Brown. Her daughter was born at 2:40 p.m. on July 23, is 20.5&nbsp;inches long and weighs seven pounds, five ounces.<ref>http://www.gopsusports.com/sports/w-baskbl/spec-rel/072309aac.html</ref> *August 21: The 2009-10 preseason candidates list for the Womenâs Wooden Award was released, naming 31 student athletes. Tyra Grant from Penn State was one of the candidates.<ref>http://www.ncaa.com/sports/w-baskbl/spec-rel/082109aaa.html</ref>
